<br>
Clerics can avoid the recast delays on their nukes by alternating two different nukes if they desire, any reason enchanters can't do the same?<br>
<br>
The only justification, as I have said many times before, is that on a raid, additional damage dealers stack, while additional utility brings diminishing returns.  This nuke is for the third and subsequent enchanters, whose support would be of little value, but whose damage would be welcome.<br>
<br>
However, that only argues that most any class should be an <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>adequate</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> damage dealer, i.e. good enough.  If clerics, enchanters, druids, and so on become all better nukers than mages, then our value to the raid, beyond the first two mages, will be in the damage our pets provide, and if that is not applicable or inadequate to the task at hand, we will find ourselves unwelcome, beyond a bot or two, on raids.<br>
<br>
This does seem wrong to me.  Barring pets, which are still unknown, we seem to get no relative improvements at all in nukes <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (nor, it seems, do wizards)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, but other classes see dramatic improvements.  While those classes deserve to be <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>adequate</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> damage dealers, we must be cautious about turning them into nukers.<br>
<br>
Remember, druids will likely get some very improved heals, perhaps complete heals, and Karana bless them for putting up with being far outclassed by others on raids, but...<br>
<br>
Even worse, this argument about nukes is to a large extent like fighting over table scraps.  If the previous three expansions are <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>any</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> indication, mobs will be tougher, have more hitpoints, melees will keep up, and casters won't.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubaramos1.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Baramos1</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 97<br> <font color=#333333>(9/20/02 11:31:30 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: an outrage, black steel &lt; insanity</span><hr size=1> Consider the total context.<br>
<br>
Our nukes only tell part of the story.  What we're talking about is damage in the final analysis.<br>
<br>
There is, simply speaking, no more powerful creature in Norrath when it comes to dealing damage, both direct and indirect, than a Mage.<br>
<br>
Our pets are a constant DoT whose mana efficiency is simply through the roof, doing damage after damage after damage, fight after fight after fight.  Nuking, hitting, stunning, bashing.  Incredible sustained direct damage.<br>
<br>
Malosini and Mala - forms of indirect damage.  Incredible debuffs that have the enemy screaming for mercy as they allow other classes to be more efficent with nukes and debuffs.  Incredibe indirect damage at low cost.<br>
<br>
Mod Rods - forms of indirect damage.  The mana transfer allows Clerics to heal, and yes, Wizards to continue to nuke more - a form of astonishing Mage indirect damage.  <br>
<br>
Damage shields.  Potent, irresistible, PBAoE damage that accounts for up to hundreds of thousands damage in long fights for a mana cost that is a drop in the bucket.  Irresistible, amazing indirect damage.<br>
<br>
Our nukes.  Direct damage of phenomenal proportion, particularly when added to the above.<br>
<br>
No, in the total context I don't see the point in making a fuss about some other class's spell with a 100 point DD difference and an absurd delay, relatively speaking.<br>
<br>
Let them have their nuke I say, and smile at the fact of our status as the most powerful damage dealing creatures who walk the land.<br>
<br>
